{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c18d84c-6da8-41e5-9283-3ebc1b315bb9","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` / `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for your process name.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile          # check path pattern\n   ulimit -c unlimited                # enable core dumps for your shell\n   ```\n   Then re-run the app. The core file is typically written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — Search the unified log for crash context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourAppName\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually your best bet — it includes the stack trace, faulting address, and signal info without any extra setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a85c5dec-491c-43d4-ac8c-d5318aeb3e3d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":324,"requestId":"502A:27A93C:2561D3:2F0837:69F55486"},"id":"f2e98e3c-7ce9-4fab-99bd-4810b74ed3eb","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:34:07.647Z","parentId":"57728bc1-695c-40f4-940d-e28576caae2d"}
